# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ionic-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Google designed Angular as a ground-up rewrite of AngularJS.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Unlike AngularJS, Angular does not have a concept of "scope" or controllers; instead, it uses a hierarchy of components as its primary architectural characteristic.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular has a different expression syntax, focusing on `"[ ]"` for property binding, and `"( )"` for event binding.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular recommends the use of Microsoft's TypeScript language, which introduces features such as static typing, generics, and type annotations.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular uses a component-based architecture, which allows developers to build encapsulated, reusable user interface elements.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Each component encapsulates its own HTML, CSS, and TypeScript, making it easier to manage and test individual pieces of an application.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular supports two-way data binding which synchronizes data between the model and the view.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] This ensures that any changes in the view are automatically reflected in the model and vice versa.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular has a built-in dependency injection system that makes it easier to manage and inject dependencies into components and services.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] This promotes modularity and easier testing.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular extends HTML with additional attributes called directives.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Directives offer functionality to change the behavior or appearance of DOM elements.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular includes a router that allows developers to define and manage application states and navigation paths, making it easier to build single-page applications with complex routing.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] The Angular CLI (Command Line Interface) provides a set of tools for creating, building, testing, and deploying Angular applications.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] It enables rapid application setup and simplifies ongoing development tasks.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular has official support for server-side rendering, which improves an application's load time and performance.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Server-side rendering also enhances search engine optimization by making content more accessible to web crawlers.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular 2.0 was announced during the keynote of the 2014 NG-Conf conference 16–17 January 2014.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] On April 30, 2015, the Angular developers announced that Angular 2 moved from Alpha to Developer Preview.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular 2 moved to Beta in December 2015, and the first release candidate was published in May 2016.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] The final version was released on 14 September 2016.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Version 8 of Angular introduced a new compilation and rendering pipeline, Ivy, and version 9 of Angular enabled Ivy by default.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular 13 removed the deprecated former compiler, View Engine.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular 14 introduced standalone components and Angular 17 made them the default, de-emphasizing the use of modules.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] The rewrite of AngularJS was called "Angular 2", but this led to confusion among developers.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] To clarify, the team announced that separate names should be used for each framework with "AngularJS" referring to the 1.X versions and "Angular" without the "JS" referring to versions 2 and up.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Since v9, the Angular team has moved all new applications to use the Ivy compiler and runtime.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] They will be working on Ivy to improve output bundle sizes and development speeds.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Each version is expected to be backward-compatible with the prior release.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] The Angular development team has pledged to do twice-a-year upgrades.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] All the major releases are supported for 18 months.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] This consists of 6 months of active support, during which regularly scheduled updates and patches are released.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] It is then followed by 12 months of long-term support (LTS), during which only critical fixes and security patches are released.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular versions v2 to v19 are no longer under support.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Analog is a full stack web meta-framework based upon Angular powered by Vite and Nitro.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular Material is a UI component library that implements Material Design in Angular.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] It provides a collection of reusable components that adhere to Google's Material Design specifications, aiming to offer a consistent user interface across different devices and platforms.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Angular Material includes a variety of UI components such as buttons, cards, dialogs, grids, and form controls.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] These components are designed to be customizable and easy to integrate into Angular applications.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] Additional features of Angular Material include support for responsive design, theming, and accessibility.
[src:ionic-framework/angular-web-framework] In 2018, Angular 6 introduced Angular Elements, enabling developers to package Angular components as custom web elements, which are part of the web components set of web platform APIs.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] The software was previously called just "PhoneGap", then "Apache Callback".
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] PhoneGap was Adobe's commercial version of Cordova along with its associated ecosystem.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] Many other tools and frameworks are also built on top of Cordova, including Ionic, Monaca, VoltBuilder, TACO, Onsen UI, GapDebug, App Builder, Cocoon, Framework7, Quasar Framework, Evothings Studio, NSB/AppStudio, Mobiscroll, and Telerik Platform.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] These tools use Cordova, and not PhoneGap for their core tools.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] Contributors to the Apache Cordova project include Adobe, BlackBerry, Google, IBM, Intel, Microsoft, Mozilla, and others.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] PhoneGap was first developed by Nitobi Software at an iPhoneDevCamp event in San Francisco in August 2008.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] Apple Inc. has confirmed that the framework has its approval, even with the change to clause 3.3.1 of the Apple iPhone SDK developer license agreement 4.0 adopted in 2010.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] The PhoneGap framework is used by several mobile application platforms such as Monaca, appMobi, Convertigo, ViziApps, and Worklight as the backbone of their mobile client development engine.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] Adobe acquired Nitobi Software on October 3, 2011.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] The PhoneGap code was subsequently contributed to the Apache Software Foundation to start a new project called Apache Cordova.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] The project's original name when submitted to the Apache Software Foundation, Callback, was changed to Cordova for ease in searching the web.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] It also appears in Adobe Systems as *Adobe PhoneGap* and also as *Adobe PhoneGap Build*.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] Early versions of PhoneGap required an Apple computer to create iOS apps and a Windows computer to create Windows Mobile apps.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] After September 2012, Adobe's PhoneGap Build service allows programmers to upload CSS, HTML, and JavaScript source code to a "cloud compiler" that generates apps for every supported platform.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] The core of an Apache Cordova application uses CSS3 and HTML5 for rendering and JavaScript for logic.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] HTML5 provides access to underlying hardware such as the accelerometer, camera, and GPS.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] However, browsers' support for HTML5-based device access is not consistent across mobile browsers, particularly older versions of Android.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] To overcome these limitations, Apache Cordova embeds the HTML5 code inside a native WebView on the device, using a foreign function interface to access the native resources of it.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] Apache Cordova can be extended with native plug-ins, allowing developers to add more functionalities that can be called from JavaScript, making it communicate directly between the native layer and the HTML5 page.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] These plugins allow access to the device's accelerometer, camera, compass, file system, microphone, and more.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] However, the use of Web-based technologies leads some Apache Cordova applications to run slower than native applications with similar functionality.
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] As of version 11, Apache Cordova currently supports development for the operating systems Apple iOS, Google Android, Windows 8.1, Windows Phone 8.1, Windows 10 and Electron (software framework) (which in turn runs on Windows, Linux and macOS).
[src:ionic-framework/apache-cordova] Earlier version of Apache Cordova used to support Bada, BlackBerry, Firefox OS, LG webOS, Microsoft Windows Phone (7 and 8), macOS, Nokia Symbian OS, Tizen (SDK 2.x), and Ubuntu Touch.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Web browsers receive HTML documents from a web server or from local storage and render the documents into multimedia web pages.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML describes the structure of a web page semantically and originally included cues for its appearance.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML elements are the building blocks of HTML pages.
[src:ionic-framework/html] With HTML constructs, images and other objects such as interactive forms may be embedded into the rendered page.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML provides a means to create structured documents by denoting structural semantics for text such as headings, paragraphs, lists, links, quotes, and other items.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML elements are delineated by *tags*, written using angle brackets.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Tags such as `<img>` and `<input>` directly introduce content into the page.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Other tags such as `<p>` and its corresponding closing tag `</p>` surround and provide information about document text and may include sub-element tags.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Browsers do not display the HTML tags, but use them to interpret the content of the page.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML can embed programs written in a scripting language such as JavaScript, which affects the behavior and content of web pages.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The inclusion of CSS defines the look and layout of content.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), former maintainer of the HTML and current maintainer of the CSS standards, has encouraged the use of CSS over explicit presentational HTML since 1997.
[src:ionic-framework/html] A form of HTML, known as HTML5, is used to display video and audio, primarily using the `<canvas>` element, together with JavaScript.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In 1980, the physicist Tim Berners-Lee, a contractor at CERN, proposed and prototyped ENQUIRE, a system for CERN researchers to use and share documents.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In 1989, Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Berners-Lee specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:ionic-framework/html] That year, Berners-Lee and CERN data systems engineer Robert Cailliau collaborated on a joint request for funding, but the project was not formally adopted by CERN.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In his personal notes of 1990, Berners-Lee listed "some of the many areas in which hypertext is used"; an encyclopedia is the first entry.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Tim Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:ionic-framework/html] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by CERN SGML, an in-house Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML)-based documentation format at CERN.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML is a markup language that web browsers use to interpret and compose text, images, and other material into visible or audible web pages.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Default characteristics for every item of HTML markup are defined in the browser, and these characteristics can be altered or enhanced by the web page designer's additional use of CSS.
[src:ionic-framework/html] These formatting commands were derived from the commands used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:ionic-framework/html] However, the SGML concept of generalized markup is based on elements (nested annotated ranges with attributes) rather than merely print effects, with separate structure and markup.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML has been progressively moved in this direction with CSS.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Berners-Lee considered HTML to be an application of SGML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The draft expired after six months, but was notable for its acknowledgment of the NCSA Mosaic browser's custom tag for embedding in-line images, reflecting the IETF's philosophy of basing standards on successful prototypes.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Similarly, Dave Raggett's competing Internet Draft, "HTML+ (Hypertext Markup Format)", from late 1993, suggested standardizing already-implemented features like tables and fill-out forms.
[src:ionic-framework/html] After the HTML and HTML+ drafts expired in early 1994, the IETF created an HTML Working Group.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In 1995, this working group completed "HTML 2.0", the first HTML specification intended to be treated as a standard against which future implementations should be based.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Further development under the auspices of the IETF was stalled by competing interests.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Since 1996, the HTML specifications have been maintained, with input from commercial software vendors, by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:ionic-framework/html] In 2000, HTML became an international standard (ISO/IEC 15445:2000).
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML 4.01 was published in late 1999, with further errata published through 2001.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In 2004, development began on HTML5 in the Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group (WHATWG), which became a joint deliverable with the W3C in 2008, and was completed and standardized on 28 October 2014.
[src:ionic-framework/html] It was the first version developed and standardized exclusively by the W3C, as the IETF had closed its HTML Working Group on 12 September 1996.
[src:ionic-framework/html] were omitted due to a mutual agreement between the two companies.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML 4 is an SGML application conforming to ISO 8879 – SGML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] was reissued with minor edits without incrementing the version number.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML", based on HTML 4.01 Strict) was published as an ISO/IEC international standard.
[src:ionic-framework/html] (ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1, Subcommittee 34 – Document description and processing languages).
[src:ionic-framework/html] After HTML 4.01, there were no new versions of HTML for many years, as the development of the parallel, XML-based language XHTML occupied the W3C's HTML Working Group.
[src:ionic-framework/html] an informal CERN document listing 18 HTML tags, was first mentioned in public.
[src:ionic-framework/html] IIIR Working Group as an Internet Draft (a rough proposal for a standard).
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML+ was published by the IETF as an Internet Draft and was a competing proposal to the Hypertext Markup Language draft.
[src:ionic-framework/html] It included many of the capabilities that were in Raggett's HTML+ proposal, such as support for tables, text flow around figures, and the display of complex mathematical formulas.
[src:ionic-framework/html] but HTML 3.0 did not succeed for several reasons.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The draft was considered very large at 150 pages and the pace of browser development, as well as the number of interested parties, had outstripped the resources of the IETF.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Browser vendors, including Microsoft and Netscape at the time, chose to implement different subsets of HTML 3's draft features as well as to introduce their own extensions to it.
[src:ionic-framework/html] has abandoned any attempt to be an SGML application and has explicitly defined its own "html" serialization, in addition to an alternative XML-based XHTML5 serialization.
[src:ionic-framework/html] On 14 February 2011, the W3C extended the charter of its HTML Working Group with clear milestones for HTML5.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In May 2011, the working group advanced HTML5 to "Last Call", an invitation to communities inside and outside W3C to confirm the technical soundness of the specification.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The W3C developed a comprehensive test suite to achieve broad interoperability for the full specification by 2014, which was the target date for recommendation.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In January 2011, the WHATWG renamed its "HTML5" living standard to "HTML".
[src:ionic-framework/html] The W3C nevertheless continued its project to release HTML5.
[src:ionic-framework/html] W3C will continue the HTML5 specification work, focusing on a single definitive standard, which is considered a "snapshot" by WHATWG.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The WHATWG organization will continue its work with HTML5 as a "Living Standard".
[src:ionic-framework/html] The concept of a living standard is that it is never complete and is always being updated and improved.
[src:ionic-framework/html] New features can be added but functionality will not be removed.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In December 2012, W3C designated HTML5 as a Candidate Recommendation.
[src:ionic-framework/html] is "two 100% complete and fully interoperable implementations".
[src:ionic-framework/html] In September 2014, W3C moved HTML5 to Proposed Recommendation.
[src:ionic-framework/html] meaning the specification process is complete.
[src:ionic-framework/html] XHTML is a separate language that began as a reformulation of HTML 4.01 using XML 1.0.
[src:ionic-framework/html] It is now referred to as *the XML syntax for HTML* and is no longer being developed as a separate standard.
[src:ionic-framework/html] On 28 May 2019, the W3C announced that WHATWG would be the sole publisher of the HTML and DOM standards.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The W3C and WHATWG had been publishing competing standards since 2012.
[src:ionic-framework/html] While the W3C standard was identical to the WHATWG in 2007 the standards have since progressively diverged due to different design decisions.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The WHATWG "Living Standard" had been the *de facto* web standard for some time.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The W3C periodically reviews and publishes snapshots of the WHATWG HTML specification as W3C Recommendations.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML markup consists of several key components, including those called *tags* (and their *attributes*), character-based *data types*, *character references* and *entity references*.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML tags most commonly come in pairs like `<h1>` and `</h1>`, although some represent *empty elements* and so are unpaired, for example `<img>`.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The first tag in such a pair is the *start tag*, and the second is the *end tag* (they are also called *opening tags* and *closing tags*).
[src:ionic-framework/html] Another important component is the HTML *document type declaration*, which triggers standards mode rendering.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The text between `<html>` and `</html>` describes the web page, and the text between `<body>` and `</body>` is the visible page content.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The markup text `<title>This is a title</title>` defines the browser page title shown on browser tabs and window titles and the tag `<div>` defines a division of the page used for easy styling.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Between `<head>` and `</head>`, a `<meta>` element can be used to define webpage metadata.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The Document Type Declaration `<!DOCTYPE html>` is for HTML5.
[src:ionic-framework/html] If a declaration is not included, various browsers will revert to "quirks mode" for rendering.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML documents imply a structure of nested HTML elements.
[src:ionic-framework/html] These are indicated in the document by HTML *tags*, enclosed in angle brackets.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In the simple, general case, the extent of an element is indicated by a pair of tags: a "start tag" `<p>` and "end tag" `</p>`.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The text content of the element, if any, is placed between these tags.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Tags may also enclose further tag markup between the start and end, including a mixture of tags and text.
[src:ionic-framework/html] This indicates further (nested) elements, as children of the parent element.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The start tag may also include the element's *attributes* within the tag.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Some elements, such as the line break `<br>` do not permit *any* embedded content, either text or further tags.
[src:ionic-framework/html] These require only a single empty tag (akin to a start tag) and do not use an end tag.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Many tags, particularly the closing end tag for the very commonly used paragraph element `<p>`, are optional.
[src:ionic-framework/html] An HTML browser or other agent can infer the closure for the end of an element from the context and the structural rules defined by the HTML standard.
[src:ionic-framework/html] These rules are complex and not widely understood by most HTML authors.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The general form of an HTML element is therefore: `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">''content''</tag>`.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Some HTML elements are defined as *empty elements* and take the form `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">`.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Empty elements may enclose no content, for instance, the `<br>` tag or the inline `<img>` tag.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The name of an HTML element is the name used in the tags.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The end tag's name is preceded by a slash character `/`.
[src:ionic-framework/html] If a tag has no content, an end tag is not allowed.
[src:ionic-framework/html] If attributes are not mentioned, default values are used in each case.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Header of the HTML document: `<head>...</head>`.
[src:ionic-framework/html] CSS can substantially change the rendering.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The difference between `<br>` and `<p>` is that `<br>` breaks a line without altering the semantic structure of the page, whereas `<p>` sections the page into paragraphs.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The element `<br>` is an *empty element* in that, although it may have attributes, it can take no content and it must not have an end tag.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The `href` attribute holds the URL address of the link.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Comments can help in the understanding of the markup and do not display in the webpage.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Most of the attributes of an element are name–value pairs, separated by `=` and written within the start tag of an element after the element's name.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The value may be enclosed in single or double quotes, although values consisting of certain characters can be left unquoted in HTML (but not XHTML).
[src:ionic-framework/html] Leaving attribute values unquoted is considered unsafe.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In contrast with name-value pair attributes, there are some attributes that affect the element simply by their presence in the start tag of the element, like the `ismap` attribute for the `img` element.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Most elements take the language-related attribute `dir` to specify text direction, such as with "rtl" for right-to-left text in, for example, Arabic, Persian or Hebrew.
[src:ionic-framework/html] As of version 4.0, HTML defines a set of 252 character entity references and a set of 1,114,050 numeric character references, both of which allow individual characters to be written via simple markup, rather than literally.
[src:ionic-framework/html] A literal character and its markup counterpart are considered equivalent and are rendered identically.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The ability to "escape" characters in this way allows for the characters `<` and `&` (when written as `&lt;` and `&amp;`, respectively) to be interpreted as character data, rather than markup.
[src:ionic-framework/html] For example, a literal `<` normally indicates the start of a tag, and `&` normally indicates the start of a character entity reference or numeric character reference; writing it as `&amp;` or `&#x26;` or `&#38;` allows `&` to be included in the content of an element or in the value of an attribute.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The double-quote character (`"`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&quot;` or `&#x22;` or `&#34;` when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Equivalently, the single-quote character (`'`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&#x27;` or `&#39;` (or as `&apos;` in HTML5 or XHTML documents) when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:ionic-framework/html] If document authors overlook the need to escape such characters, some browsers can be very forgiving and try to use context to guess their intent.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The result is still invalid markup, which makes the document less accessible to other browsers and to other user agents that may try to parse the document for search and indexing purposes for example.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Escaping also allows for characters that are not easily typed, or that are not available in the document's character encoding, to be represented within the element and attribute content.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Unicode character encodings such as UTF-8 are compatible with all modern browsers and allow direct access to almost all the characters of the world's writing systems.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML defines several data types for element content, such as script data and stylesheet data, and a plethora of types for attribute values, including IDs, names, URIs, numbers, units of length, languages, media descriptors, colors, character encodings, dates and times, and so on.
[src:ionic-framework/html] All of these data types are specializations of character data.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML documents are required to start with a document type declaration (informally, a "doctype").
[src:ionic-framework/html] In browsers, the doctype helps to define the rendering mode—particularly whether to use quirks mode.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The original purpose of the doctype was to enable the parsing and validation of HTML documents by SGML tools based on the document type definition (DTD).
[src:ionic-framework/html] The DTD to which the DOCTYPE refers contains a machine-readable grammar specifying the permitted and prohibited content for a document conforming to such a DTD.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Browsers, on the other hand, do not implement HTML as an application of SGML and as consequence do not read the DTD.
[src:ionic-framework/html] This declaration references the DTD for the "strict" version of HTML 4.01.
[src:ionic-framework/html] SGML-based validators read the DTD in order to properly parse the document and to perform validation.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In modern browsers, a valid doctype activates standards mode as opposed to quirks mode.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In addition, HTML 4.01 provides Transitional and Frameset DTDs, as explained below.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The transitional type is the most inclusive, incorporating current tags as well as older or "deprecated" tags, with the Strict DTD excluding deprecated tags.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The frameset has all tags necessary to make frames on a page along with the tags included in transitional type.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Semantic HTML is a way of writing HTML that emphasizes the meaning of the encoded information over its presentation (look).
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML has included semantic markup from its inception, but has also included presentational markup, such as `<font>`, `<i>`, and `<center>` tags.
[src:ionic-framework/html] There are also the semantically neutral div and span tags.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Since the late 1990s, when Cascading Style Sheets were beginning to work in most browsers, web authors have been encouraged to avoid the use of presentational HTML markup with a view to the separation of content and presentation.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In a 2001 discussion of the Semantic Web, Tim Berners-Lee and others gave examples of ways in which intelligent software "agents" may one day automatically crawl the web and find, filter, and correlate previously unrelated, published facts for the benefit of human users.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Such agents are not commonplace even now, but some of the ideas of Web 2.0, mashups and price comparison websites may be coming close.
[src:ionic-framework/html] An important type of web agent that does crawl and read web pages automatically, without prior knowledge of what it might find, is the web crawler or search-engine spider.
[src:ionic-framework/html] These software agents are dependent on the semantic clarity of web pages they find as they use various techniques and algorithms to read and index millions of web pages a day and provide web users with search facilities without which the World Wide Web's usefulness would be greatly reduced.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Presentational markup tags are deprecated in current HTML and XHTML recommendations.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The majority of presentational features from previous versions of HTML are no longer allowed as they lead to poorer accessibility, higher cost of site maintenance, and larger document sizes.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Good semantic HTML also improves the accessibility of web documents (see also Web Content Accessibility Guidelines).
[src:ionic-framework/html] For example, when a screen reader or audio browser can correctly ascertain the structure of a document, it will not waste the visually impaired user's time by reading out repeated or irrelevant information when it has been marked up correctly.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML documents can be delivered by the same means as any other computer file.
[src:ionic-framework/html] However, they are most often delivered either by HTTP from a web server or by email.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The World Wide Web is composed primarily of HTML documents transmitted from web servers to web browsers using the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:ionic-framework/html] However, HTTP is used to serve images, sound, and other content, in addition to HTML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] To allow the web browser to know how to handle each document it receives, other information is transmitted along with the document.
[src:ionic-framework/html] This meta data usually includes the MIME type (e.g., text/html or application/xhtml+xml) and the character encoding (see Character encodings in HTML).
[src:ionic-framework/html] In modern browsers, the MIME type that is sent with the HTML document may affect how the document is initially interpreted.
[src:ionic-framework/html] A document sent with the XHTML MIME type is expected to be well-formed XML; syntax errors may cause the browser to fail to render it.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The same document sent with the HTML MIME type might be displayed successfully since some browsers are more lenient with HTML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The W3C recommendations state that XHTML 1.0 documents that follow guidelines set forth in the recommendation's Appendix C may be labeled with either MIME Type.
[src:ionic-framework/html] XHTML 1.1 also states that XHTML 1.1 documents should be labeled with either MIME type.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Most graphical email clients allow the use of a subset of HTML (often ill-defined) to provide formatting and semantic markup not available with plain text.
[src:ionic-framework/html] This may include typographic information like colored headings, emphasized and quoted text, inline images and diagrams.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Many such clients include both a GUI editor for composing HTML e-mail messages and a rendering engine for displaying them.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Use of HTML in e-mail is criticized by some because of compatibility issues, because it can help disguise phishing attacks, because of accessibility issues for blind or visually impaired people, because it can confuse spam filters and because the message size is larger than plain text.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The most common filename extension for files containing HTML is .html.
[src:ionic-framework/html] A common abbreviation of this is .htm, which originated because some operating systems limit file extensions to three letters.
[src:ionic-framework/html] An HTML Application (HTA; file extension .hta) is a Microsoft Windows application that uses HTML and Dynamic HTML in a browser to provide the application's graphical interface.
[src:ionic-framework/html] A regular HTML file is confined to the security model of the web browser's security, communicating only to web servers and manipulating only web page objects and site cookies.
[src:ionic-framework/html] An HTA runs as a fully trusted application and therefore has more privileges, like creation/editing/removal of files and Windows Registry entries.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Because they operate outside the browser's security model, HTAs cannot be executed via HTTP, but must be downloaded (just like an EXE file) and executed from local file system.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Since its inception, HTML and its associated protocols gained acceptance relatively quickly.
[src:ionic-framework/html] However, no clear standards existed in the early years of the language.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Though its creators originally conceived of HTML as a semantic language devoid of presentation details, practical uses pushed many presentational elements and attributes into the language, driven largely by the various browser vendors.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The latest standards surrounding HTML reflect efforts to overcome the sometimes chaotic development of the language and to create a rational foundation for building both meaningful and well-presented documents.
[src:ionic-framework/html] To return HTML to its role as a semantic language, the W3C has developed style languages such as CSS and XSL to shoulder the burden of presentation.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In conjunction, the HTML specification has slowly reined in the presentational elements.
[src:ionic-framework/html] There are two axes differentiating various variations of HTML as currently specified: SGML-based HTML versus XML-based HTML (referred to as XHTML) on one axis, and strict versus transitional (loose) versus frameset on the other axis.
[src:ionic-framework/html] One difference in the latest HTML specifications lies in the distinction between the SGML-based specification and the XML-based specification.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The XML-based specification is usually called XHTML to distinguish it clearly from the more traditional definition.
[src:ionic-framework/html] However, the root element name continues to be "html" even in the XHTML-specified HTML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The W3C intended XHTML 1.0 to be identical to HTML 4.01 except where limitations of XML over the more complex SGML require workarounds.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Because XHTML and HTML are closely related, they are sometimes documented in parallel.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In such circumstances, some authors conflate the two names as (X)HTML or X(HTML).
[src:ionic-framework/html] Like HTML 4.01, XHTML 1.0 has three sub-specifications: strict, transitional, and frameset.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Aside from the different opening declarations for a document, the differences between an HTML 4.01 and XHTML 1.0 document—in each of the corresponding DTDs—are largely syntactic.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The underlying syntax of HTML allows many shortcuts that XHTML does not, such as elements with optional opening or closing tags, and even empty elements which must not have an end tag.
[src:ionic-framework/html] By contrast, XHTML requires all elements to have an opening tag and a closing tag.
[src:ionic-framework/html] XHTML, however, also introduces a new shortcut: an XHTML tag may be opened and closed within the same tag, by including a slash before the end of the tag like this: `<br/>`.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The introduction of this shorthand, which is not used in the SGML declaration for HTML 4.01, may confuse earlier software unfamiliar with this new convention.
[src:ionic-framework/html] A fix for this is remove the slash preceding the closing angle bracket, as such: `<br>`.
[src:ionic-framework/html] To understand the subtle differences between HTML and XHTML, consider the transformation of a valid and well-formed XHTML 1.0 document that adheres to Appendix C (see below) into a valid HTML 4.01 document.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Change the document type declaration from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Ensure that the document's MIME type is set to `text/html`.
[src:ionic-framework/html] For both HTML and XHTML, this comes from the HTTP `Content-Type` header sent by the server.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Change the XML empty-element syntax to an HTML style empty element (`<br/>` to `<br>`).
[src:ionic-framework/html] Those are the main changes necessary to translate a document from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:ionic-framework/html] To translate from HTML to XHTML would also require the addition of any omitted opening or closing tags.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Whether coding in HTML or XHTML it may just be best to always include the optional tags within an HTML document rather than remembering which tags can be omitted.
[src:ionic-framework/html] A well-formed XHTML document adheres to all the syntax requirements of XML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] A valid document adheres to the content specification for XHTML, which describes the document structure.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The W3C recommends several conventions to ensure an easy migration between HTML and XHTML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] By carefully following the W3C's compatibility guidelines, a user agent should be able to interpret the document equally as HTML or XHTML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] For documents that are XHTML 1.0 and have been made compatible in this way, the W3C permits them to be served either as HTML (with a `text/html` MIME type), or as XHTML (with an `application/xhtml+xml` or `application/xml` MIME type).
[src:ionic-framework/html] When delivered as XHTML, browsers should use an XML parser, which adheres strictly to the XML specifications for parsing the document's contents.
[src:ionic-framework/html] HTML 4 defined three different versions of the language: Strict, Transitional (once called Loose), and Frameset.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The Strict version is intended for new documents and is considered best practice, while the Transitional and Frameset versions were developed to make it easier to transition documents that conformed to older HTML specifications or did not conform to any specification to a version of HTML 4.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The Transitional and Frameset versions allow for presentational markup, which is omitted in the Strict version.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Instead, cascading style sheets are encouraged to improve the presentation of HTML documents.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Because XHTML 1 only defines an XML syntax for the language defined by HTML 4, the same differences apply to XHTML 1 as well.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The Frameset version includes everything in the Transitional version, as well as the `frameset` element (used instead of `body`) and the `frame` element.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In addition to the above transitional differences, the frameset specifications (whether XHTML 1.0 or HTML 4.01) specify a different content model, with `frameset` replacing `body`, that contains either `frame` elements, or optionally `noframes` with a `body`.
[src:ionic-framework/html] As this list demonstrates, the loose versions of the specification are maintained for legacy support.
[src:ionic-framework/html] However, contrary to popular misconceptions, the move to XHTML does not imply a removal of this legacy support.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Rather the X in XML stands for extensible and the W3C is modularizing the entire specification and opens it up to independent extensions.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The primary achievement in the move from XHTML 1.0 to XHTML 1.1 is the modularization of the entire specification.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The strict version of HTML is deployed in XHTML 1.1 through a set of modular extensions to the base XHTML 1.1 specification.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Likewise, someone looking for the loose (transitional) or frameset specifications will find similar extended XHTML 1.1 support (much of it is contained in the legacy or frame modules).
[src:ionic-framework/html] Modularization also allows for separate features to develop on their own timetable.
[src:ionic-framework/html] So for example, XHTML 1.1 will allow quicker migration to emerging XML standards such as MathML (a presentational and semantic math language based on XML) and XForms—a new highly advanced web-form technology to replace the existing HTML forms.
[src:ionic-framework/html] In summary, the HTML 4 specification primarily reined in all the various HTML implementations into a single clearly written specification based on SGML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] XHTML 1.0, ported this specification, as is, to the new XML-defined specification.
[src:ionic-framework/html] Next, XHTML 1.1 takes advantage of the extensible nature of XML and modularizes the whole specification.
[src:ionic-framework/html] XHTML 2.0 was intended to be the first step in adding new features to the specification in a standards-body-based approach.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The HTML Living Standard, which is developed by WHATWG, is the official version, while W3C HTML5 is no longer separate from WHATWG.
[src:ionic-framework/html] WYSIWYG editors (*what you see is what you get*), are HTML editors in which the user lays out everything as it is to appear in the HTML document using a graphical user interface (GUI), such as Microsoft FrontPage, often similar to word processors.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The editor renders the document rather than showing the code, so authors do not require extensive knowledge of HTML.
[src:ionic-framework/html] The WYSIWYG editing model has been criticized, primarily because of the low quality of the generated code; there are various developers advocating a change to the WYSIWYM model (*what you see is what you mean*).
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] A **web application** (or **web app**) is application software that is created with web technologies and runs via a web browser.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Web applications emerged during the late 1990s and allowed for the server to dynamically build a response to the request, in contrast to static web pages.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Web applications are commonly distributed via a web server.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] There are several different tier systems that web applications use to communicate between the web browsers, the client interface, and server data.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Each system has its own uses as they function in different ways.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] However, there are many security risks that developers must be aware of during development; proper measures to protect user data are vital.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Web applications are often constructed with the use of a web application framework.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Single-page applications (SPAs) and progressive web apps (PWAs) are two architectural approaches to creating web applications that provide a user experience similar to native apps, including features such as smooth navigation, offline support, and faster interactions.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Modern browsers such as Chrome offer sandboxing for every browser tab which improves security and restricts access to local resources.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] No software installation is required as the app runs within the browser which reduces the need for managing software installations.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] With the use of remote cloud services, customers do not need to manage servers as that can be left to the developer and the cloud service and can use the software with a relatively low power, low-resource PC such as a thin client.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] The source code of the application can stay the same across operating systems and devices of users with the use of responsive web design, since it only needs to be compatible with web browsers which adhere to web standards, making the code highly portable and saving on development time.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Numerous JavaScript frameworks and CSS frameworks facilitate development.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] The concept of a "web application" was first introduced in the Java language in the Servlet Specification version 2.2, which was released in 1999.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] At that time, both JavaScript and XML had already been developed, but the XMLHttpRequest object had only been recently introduced on Internet Explorer 5 as an ActiveX object.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Beginning around the early 2000s, applications such as "Myspace (2003), Gmail (2004), Digg (2004), [and] Google Maps (2005)," started to make their client sides more and more interactive.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] A web page script is able to contact the server for storing/retrieving data without downloading an entire web page.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] The practice became known as Ajax in 2005.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Eventually this was replaced by web APIs using JSON, accessed via JavaScript asynchronously on the client side.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] In earlier computing models like client-server, the processing load for the application was shared between code on the server and code installed on each client locally.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] In other words, an application had its own pre-compiled client program which served as its user interface and had to be separately installed on each user's personal computer.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] An upgrade to the server-side code of the application would typically also require an upgrade to the client-side code installed on each user workstation, adding to the support cost and decreasing productivity.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Additionally, both the client and server components of the application were bound tightly to a particular computer architecture and operating system, which made porting them to other systems prohibitively expensive for all but the largest applications.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Later, in 1995, Netscape introduced the client-side scripting language called JavaScript, which allowed programmers to add dynamic elements to the user interface that ran on the client side.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Essentially, instead of sending data to the server in order to generate an entire web page, the embedded scripts of the downloaded page can perform various tasks such as input validation or showing/hiding parts of the page.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Traditional PC applications are typically single-tiered, residing solely on the client machine.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] In contrast, web applications inherently facilitate a multi-tiered architecture.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Though many variations are possible, the most common structure is the three-tiered application.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] In its most common form, the three tiers are called *presentation*, *application* and *storage*.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] The first tier, presentation, refers to a web browser itself.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] The second tier refers to any engine using dynamic web content technology (such as ASP, CGI, ColdFusion, Dart, JSP/Java, Node.js, PHP, Python or Ruby on Rails).
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] The third tier refers to a database that stores data and determines the structure of a user interface.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Essentially, when using the three-tiered system, the web browser sends requests to the engine, which then services them by making queries and updates against the database and generates a user interface.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] The 3-tier solution may fall short when dealing with more complex applications, and may need to be replaced with the n-tiered approach; the greatest benefit of which is how business logic (which resides on the application tier) is broken down into a more fine-grained model.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Another benefit would be to add an integration tier, which separates the data tier and provides an easy-to-use interface to access the data.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] For example, the client data would be accessed by calling a "list_clients()" function instead of making an SQL query directly against the client table on the database.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] This allows the underlying database to be replaced without making any change to the other tiers.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] There are some who view a web application as a two-tier architecture.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] This can be a "smart" client that performs all the work and queries a "dumb" server, or a "dumb" client that relies on a "smart" server.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] The client would handle the presentation tier, the server would have the database (storage tier), and the business logic (application tier) would be on one of them or on both.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] While this increases the scalability of the applications and separates the display and the database, it still does not allow for true specialization of layers, so most applications will outgrow this model.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Security breaches on these kinds of applications are a major concern because it can involve both enterprise information and private customer data.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Protecting these assets is an important part of any web application, and there are some key operational areas that must be included in the development process.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] This includes processes for authentication, authorization, asset handling, input, and logging and auditing.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Building security into the applications from the beginning is sometimes more effective and less disruptive in the long run.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] Writing web applications is simplified with the use of web application frameworks.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] These frameworks facilitate rapid application development by allowing a development team to focus on the parts of their application which are unique to their goals without having to resolve common development issues such as user management.
[src:ionic-framework/hybrid-app] In addition, there is potential for the development of applications on Internet operating systems, although currently there are not many viable platforms that fit this model.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic was created by Drifty Co. in 2013.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] After releasing an alpha version of the framework in November 2013, a 1.0 beta was released in March 2014, a 1.0 final in May 2015, and several 2.0 releases in 2016.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Since January 2019, Ionic 4 allows developers to choose other frameworks apart from Angular like React, Vue.js, and web components.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic was acquired by OutSystems in November 2022.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic uses Cordova and, more recently, Capacitor plugins to gain access to host operating systems features such as Camera, GPS, Flashlight, etc.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Users can build their apps, and they can then be customized for Android, iOS, Windows, Desktop (with Electron), or modern browsers.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic allows app building and deployment by wrapping around the build tool Cordova or Capacitor with a simplified 'ionic' command line tool.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic includes mobile components, typography, interactive paradigms, and an extensible base theme.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Using Web Components, Ionic provides custom components and methods for interacting with them.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] One such component, virtual scroll, allows users to scroll through a list of thousands of items without any performance hits.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Another component, tabs, creates a tabbed interface with support for native-style navigation and history state management.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Besides the SDK, Ionic also provides services that developers can use to enable features, such as code deploys, automated builds.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic also provides its own IDE known as Ionic Studio, but it was discontinued in 2020.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic also provides a command-line interface (CLI) to create projects.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] The CLI also allows developers to add Cordova plugins and additional front-end packages, enable push notifications, generate app Icons and Splash screens, and build native binaries.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] For Android, Ionic supports Android 4.4 and up.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic 2 supports the Universal Windows Platform for building Windows 10 apps.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic Framework, based on *Angular.js*, supports BlackBerry 10 apps.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic apps run with a mixture of native code and web code, providing full access to native functionality if necessary, with the bulk of the UI of the app built with standard web technology.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic utilizes native hardware acceleration features available in the browser (such as CSS animations) and optimizes rendering (avoiding expensive DOM manipulation).
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic leverages CSS transitions and transforms for animation as a way to leverage the GPU and maximize available processor time.
[src:ionic-framework/ionic-mobile-app-framework] Ionic is an npm module and requires Node.js.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] A **progressive web application** (**PWA**), or **progressive web app**, is a type of web app that can be installed on a device as a standalone application.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] PWAs are installed using the offline cache of the device's web browser.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] PWAs were introduced from 2016 as an alternative to native (device-specific) applications, with the advantage that they do not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] They can be used on a range of different systems, including desktop and mobile devices.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Publishing the app to digital distribution systems, such as the Apple App Store, Google Play, or the Microsoft Store on Windows, is optional.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Because a PWA is delivered in the form of a webpage or website built using common web technologies including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and WebAssembly, it can work on any platform with a PWA-compatible browser.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] As of 2025, PWA features are supported to varying degrees by Google Chrome, Apple Safari, Brave, Firefox for Android, Microsoft Edge, and Firefox for Windows.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] At Apple's Worldwide Developers Conference in 2007, Steve Jobs announced that the iPhone would "run applications created with Web 2.0 Internet standards".
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] No software development kit (SDK) was required, and the apps would be fully integrated into the device through the Safari browser engine.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] This model was later switched to the App Store, as a means of appeasing frustrated developers.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] In October 2007 Jobs announced that an SDK would be launched the following year.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] As a result, although Apple continued to support web apps, the vast majority of iOS applications shifted toward the App Store.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Beginning in the early 2010s dynamic web pages allowed web technologies to be used to create interactive web applications.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Responsive web design, and the screen-size flexibility it provides have made PWA development more accessible.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Continued enhancements to HTML, CSS, and JavaScript allowed web applications to incorporate greater levels of interactivity, making native-like experiences possible on a website.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] It was intended to be an open-source operating system for running web apps as native apps on mobile devices.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Firefox OS was based on the Gecko rendering engine with a user interface called Gaia, written in HTML5.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] The development of Firefox OS ended in 2016, and the project was completely discontinued in 2017, although a fork of Firefox OS was used as the basis of KaiOS, a feature phone platform.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Google then put significant efforts into promoting PWA development for Android.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Firefox introduced support for service workers in 2016, and Microsoft Edge and Apple Safari followed in 2018, making service workers available on all major systems.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] By 2019, PWAs were supported by desktop versions of some browsers, including Microsoft Edge (on Windows) and Google Chrome (on Windows, macOS, ChromeOS, and Linux).
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] In December 2020, Firefox for desktop abandoned the implementation of PWAs (specifically, removed the prototype "site-specific browser" configuration that had been available as an experimental feature).
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] A Firefox architect noted: "The signal I hope we are sending is that PWA support is not coming to desktop Firefox anytime soon." Mozilla supports PWAs on Android and plans to keep supporting it.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Firefox version 143.0, released in September 2025, added support for PWA on Windows.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps are all designed to work on any browser that is compliant with the appropriate web standards.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] As with other cross-platform solutions, the goal is to help developers build cross-platform apps more easily than they would with native apps.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps employ the progressive enhancement web development strategy.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Some progressive web apps use an architectural approach called the App Shell Model.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] In this model, service workers store the Basic User Interface or "shell" of the responsive web design web application in the browser's offline cache.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] This model allows for PWAs to maintain native-like use with or without web connectivity.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] This can improve loading time, by providing an *initial static frame*, a layout or architecture into which content can be loaded progressively as well as dynamically.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] There are many technologies commonly used to create progressive web apps.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] A web application is considered a PWA if it satisfies the installation criteria, thus can work offline and can be added to the device's home screen.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] To meet this definition, all PWAs require at minimum a manifest and a service worker.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Other technologies may be used to store data, communicate with servers or execute code.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] This metadata is crucial for an app to be added to a home screen or otherwise listed alongside native apps.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] iOS Safari partially implements manifests, while most of the PWA metadata can be defined via Apple-specific extensions to the meta tags.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] These tags allow developers to enable full-screen display, define icons and splash screens, and specify a name for the application.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] A service worker is a web worker that implements a programmable network proxy that can respond to web/HTTP requests from the main document.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] It is able to check the availability of a remote server, cache content when that server is available, and serve that content to the document later.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Service workers, like any other web workers, work separately from the main document context.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Service workers can handle push notifications and synchronize data in the background, cache or retrieve resource requests, intercept network requests and receive centralized updates independently of the document that registered them, even when that document is not loaded.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Service workers go through a three-step lifecycle of Registration, Installation and Activation.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Registration involves telling the browser the location of the service worker in preparation for installation.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Installation occurs when there is no service worker installed in the browser for the web app, or if there is an update to the service worker.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Activation occurs when all of the PWA's pages are closed, so that there is no conflict between the previous version and the updated one.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] The lifecycle also helps maintain consistency when switching among versions of a service worker since only a single service worker can be active for a domain.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] WebAssembly allows precompiled code to run in a web browser, at near-native speed.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Thus, libraries written in languages such as C can be added to web apps.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Announced in 2015 and first released in March 2017, WebAssembly became a W3C recommendation on December 5, 2019 and it received the Programming Languages Software Award from ACM SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] is a WHATWG standard API that enables key–value storage in modern browsers.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] (that enables storage that persists across sessions).
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] is a W3C standard database API available in all major browsers.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] objects and any structures representable as a string.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] providing additional constructs around it.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] In 2017, Twitter released Twitter Lite, a PWA alternative to the official native Android and iOS apps.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] According to Twitter, Twitter Lite consumed only 1–3% of the size of the native apps.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Starbucks provides a PWA that is 99.84% smaller than its equivalent iOS app.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] After deploying its PWA, Starbucks doubled the number of online orders, with desktop users ordering at about the same rate as mobile app users.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] A 2018 review published by Forbes, found that users of Pinterest's PWA spent 40% more time on the site compared to the previous mobile website.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Ad revenue rates also increased by 44%, and core engagements by 60%.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Flipkart saw 60% of customers who had uninstalled their native app return to use the Flipkart PWA.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Lancôme saw an 84% decrease in time until the page is interactive, leading to a 17% increase in conversions and a 53% increase in mobile sessions on iOS with their PWA.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Since a PWA does not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms and is available to users via the web, it is not necessary for developers to release it over digital distribution systems like the Apple App Store, Google Play, Microsoft Store, or Samsung Galaxy Store.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] The major app stores support the publication of PWAs to varying degrees.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Google Play, Microsoft Store, and Samsung Galaxy Store support PWAs, but Apple App Store does not.
[src:ionic-framework/progressive-web-app] Microsoft Store publishes some qualifying PWAs automatically (even without app authors' requests) after discovering them via Bing indexing.
